segments.text: What are you doing up there?
It sounded like a good idea.
That's what I got the idea.
At a meeting, came into the meeting.
Remember, the two boys were ready to go.
I had a pity the judge
At that time, I asked me to go.
I didn't want to go home.
He said, I'm sure you got him.
So, he began, bam, more pain, bam, bam, bam, like a thing.
I can't make sure the association was that way of that.
I mean, he said, well, I need you what we've done.
He said, I don't know, take any more.
Turn them down, and they had help with them.
When you met with Governor Daniels before he appointed you to the A&M board, you said that you promised him you would not vote for co-education while he was governor.
Did he ask you any other questions?
I said, everybody, I'm going to work against me.
I said that I click at him.
Now, he was not necessarily opposed to co-education, was he?
Didn't he think it was just politically dangerous?
Had you known Governor Daniel a long time?
And you all had worked together before then?
Now, was it Governor Connolly that reappointed you?
Did you all have a conversation before he didn't call you up or anything or quiz you, interview you?
In those 12 years, did the governor call you during your service to talk about A&M?
Did you go to the legislature to lobby for A&M during those years?
I checked him as soon as he got out of his head.
Now, Bill Moore as senator was a strong advocate for A&M.
Do you remember Brownrig Dewey, the state representative from Brazos County then?
He was a small, kind of quiet man, but he was in the House of Representatives.
Were there any strong opponents in the legislature of .
While you were on the board, was Mrs. Cashin still the hostess at the board house?
Because I interviewed one of her sons the other day, Jim.
And he was telling me that after his father died, that for many years she was the hostess at the board house north of Cebisa.
Now, when you all had board meetings, did you meet at the MSC or at the board house?
I had room at our meeting.
I got a good one now.
Let me ask about some other people.
Tiger Teague, was he a good ally for A&M?
What did he work hardest for?
Lupo, that ran the store at Northgate, he was a classmate of Mr. Rudder and Mr. Teague's, and he loaned money to students always.
I remember him as a when I got there he was a kind of a frail little man but always had a smile
and had lots of energy, and was always going around shaking hands and patting people on the back.
Mr. Zachary, I know he was a classmate.
when he was on the board, was he a strong supporter of change?
Oh, he was not for co-education?
But he did care about A&M very deeply.
And we understand that his son may soon be appointed to the board.
We talked about Buck Shewitch yesterday.
When Buck was a student, was he large in weight as he would later be, or was he kind of trim?
One of the best friends I am.
If you ever decide you want to sell any of your Shewitz items, I want to bid for them because my wife and I knew him, and we collect Shewitz items.
Buck was such a special guy.
Tom Harrington, you knew him as a student.
I knew him as a student.
What kind of student was he?

My earliest years, we lived in Garland, and when we needed anything fixed on the Farmall tractor, we went to Plano because the Harrington family owned that, and I believe a funeral home and I think a furniture store.
And the Harrington family was very, very good.
As time came to consider co-education and volunteer corps, was Dr. Harrington supportive of those changes?
I hadn't thought about that, that he would have to follow the board.
Dick Hervey, as executive director of the former students, was he a strong advocate for A&M?
Because you and Dick worked closely together, didn't you?
The former student association has been very blessed to have such good leadership.
And now with Randy Mattson, Randy's one of my favorites.
I met him the day that John Lindsay brought him to A&M to try to recruit him as a student.
In high school, he was All-State.
Then he played one year of basketball at A&M and was very, very good.
Basically, he's a good, solid human being.
You were in the Corps of Cadets.
What did you learn from that experience?
What did being in the Corps teach you?
To be on time, I guess.
I don't love them, but time meant a lot.
Describe the uniforms that you all wore when you were a student.
What did the uniforms look like then?
Was it a gray shirt then?
Did y'all wear the high senior boots?
It feels like, so I gotta have... I gotta... I gotta... I gotta... I gotta... I gotta... I gotta...
Did you call your roommates fish old ladies then?
Did you all have a lot of slang?
Do you remember any of it?
Did the teachers, the faculty members have nicknames then?
I was going to, okay, pull my key.
And I was like, yeah, she's going to exercise.
I was going to pull my key.
Anyway, I remember going out and changing courses in winter.
So I went out one night.
He gave us a picture about how I did the best I could on it.
And then he said, bitch, you're doing a real good job.
Anyway, at the end of the serve,
He had trouble up the jam with him.
Cleaned out the board, damn it, big shovel.
I told him later about what he was like right now.
Anyway, I ended up with a friend of mine, a great friend of mine.
He kept cleaning up the bar.
Now, what were your favorite courses?
What subjects did you most enjoy at A&M?
Wanted to make 100 and you did.
What were the hardest courses for you?
The ones that you had to work the hardest.
You mentioned yesterday Tommy Mayo as the fine librarian.
Did he teach any courses then in English?
Tommy Mayo, one of the best instructors I had.
Now, that wasn't a secret society, was it?
Hadn't came into it so far again.
Probably about four or three people.
How often did the Gento meet?
Did each of you sometimes give the program?
I had an argument about that.
I got the best course I had.
Dana Bible, the coach, the star of the football team.
Coach Dana X. Bible was the football coach.
But I don't remember who the basketball coach was.
Let's see, did I ask you if you knew Heine Weir?
He later taught at Schreiner in Kerrville.
And let's see, did you know King Gill?
But he wasn't as big as Weir, was he?
Was Gil a good football player?
Was Coach Bible an excellent coach?
Did he relate well to students?
because to me the Twelfth Man story revolves around him.
Whether it's a legend or a fact, it still relates around him.
When did people begin to talk about the Twelfth Man?
Did anybody ever get into biscuit fights and throw biscuits?
Did y'all behave well in Cebisa?
Seniors would do something about that.
Oh, seniors would do something about that?
Now, when they paddled you, when did they do it?
And then where would that happen?
Did the sophomores do the paddling or the seniors?
Does your love for the library, does Tommy Mayo help to stimulate that?
See, I think that's a good proof that the good works of people can live a long, long time.
Like my office is in the Evans Library, so each day when I go to my office, I am proud to say that I have an acquaintance with you.
What did you all do at the Y?
Was there a pool hall in there?
So an indoor swimming pool, pool hall.
Were you all allowed to play cards?
In class, did you ever sleep through class and not go to class?
What would happen if somebody went to sleep in class?
They'd eat that lunch for a freshman.
Now, you graduated in four years.
During that time, do you remember any famous people coming to the campus?
Did General Pershing, by chance, did he come?
Guyon Hall was the big assembly room.
Did you all have worship services in there?
And who would lead the service?
Was there a chaplain for the... Did you all have a religious emphasis week?
In the 1950s, there was religious emphasis week.
Did you go to church while you were a student?
Had you been a church member before you went away?
So you were fully immersed and washed clean.
Were there any tragic events that happened to any of your friends while you were at A&M?
Most of your friends, were they from the city or were they from small towns?
And were they farm boys or ranch boys?
Was DeWare Fieldhouse, was it built yet, the basketball?
DeWare Fieldhouse, was it built yet?
The football was played at Kyle Field.
I had a friend that you had worked with a corporation.
He said, I'm going to get you one corporation commissioner.
I tried to port a fellow to bang him so that you know.
So he ran his order or whatever.
